data.content:
Your code **does not use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, or catch `ThreadAbortException`. It only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — all of which work identically in .NET 8. **No migration is needed for Thread.Abort concerns.**

That said, the idiomatic .NET 8 approach would replace raw threads with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.WhenAll`:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        Parallel.ForEach(items, item =>
        {
            item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
        });
    }
}
```

This gives you automatic thread pool management and better scalability, but it's a modernization choice — not a required migration fix.
